  {
    "index": 3,
    "hash": "1W4hbURe4ksNyfZNtWlnksNOPl4=",
    "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:31.000Z",
    "action": {
      "type": "SET_CONTENT",
      "input": {
        "content": "Connect-on-Swarm data is distributed across four layers with distinct durability properties:\n\n**Layer 1 \u2014 PGlite (browser, ephemeral)**: Operations, documents, relationships, keyframes. Survives page refresh via IndexedDB, lost on \"Clear site data\", new device, or new browser.\n\n**Layer 2 \u2014 Swarm /bytes (immutable, permanent until stamp expires)**: Encrypted operation batches and manifest payloads. Content-addressed (uploading the same data twice produces the same reference), replicated across the neighborhood. Lost only when stamps expire and chunks are evicted from reserves.\n\n**Layer 3 \u2014 Swarm feeds (mutable pointers)**: 64-char hex references pointing to /bytes data. Each feed index is write-once; the feed as a whole is append-only. One feed per topic. Same durability as /bytes.\n\n**Layer 4 \u2014 IndexedDB caches (browser, ephemeral helpers)**: Manifest index (docId -> latest /bytes ref, for bee dev mode), pending ops buffer, wallet-derived signer key cache. Survives page refresh, lost on \"Clear site data\".\n\nEach layer has a specific role: PGlite is the hot read path, /bytes is the durable payload store, feeds are the mutable lookup, and IndexedDB accelerates repeated lookups.",
        "updatedAt": "2026-05-13T13:00:31.000Z"
      },
      "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:31.000Z"
    }
  },
